      {
        "id" : "d15443ff-f60a-47f8-8a90-89652d30ae2d",
        "parentId" : null,
        "authorId" : "0474385d-5aae-4093-b7fc-7f38665f8960",
        "body" : "Is there a reason that the second tap has to be `startGesture` instead of `tap`?   Is this way faster?",
        "createdAt" : "2019-11-08T01:03:35Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-11-08T01:03:51Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "0474385d-5aae-4093-b7fc-7f38665f8960",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "012d2ff2-ff62-47ad-8fd4-8506d3ca8a49",
        "parentId" : "d15443ff-f60a-47f8-8a90-89652d30ae2d",
        "authorId" : "a28d4bf0-9b21-4633-a08e-c383b294a037",
        "body" : "The sequence of events that leads to this bug is: \r\n\r\n- The first tap finishes, `setState` gets called in the user callback.\r\n- The tap down event of the second tap happens\r\n- The segmented control gets rebuilt with the new `groupValue`\r\n- The tap up event of the second tap happens.\r\n\r\nThe test basically follows these steps so the second tap had to be broken up into a tap down and a tap up event.",
        "createdAt" : "2019-11-08T01:23:36Z",
        "updatedAt" : "2019-11-08T18:05:12Z",
        "lastEditedBy" : "a28d4bf0-9b21-4633-a08e-c383b294a037",
        "tags" : [
        ]
      },
      {
        "id" : "23d35a81-26b7-4b8e-b5f2-cafafe2792bc",
